NFC Tag Technical Code Documentation for GitHub
Introduction
NFC tags are passive, unpowered chips operating at 13.56 MHz (ISO/IEC 18000-3/14443) that store small data payloads (URLs, Wi-Fi credentials, etc.) and communicate via magnetic induction. This documentation provides technical implementation details and code examples for interacting with NFC tags using Python, focusing on NTAG21x series chips compatible with modern smartphones.

Technical Specifications
Chip Types: NTAG213 (144 bytes), NTAG215 (504 bytes), NTAG216 (888 bytes)
Communication Protocol: ISO/IEC 14443 Type A with NDEF Type 2 format
Range: ≤4cm contactless interaction
Security: 32-bit password protection, lockable memory sectors
Smartphone Compatibility: Apple Shortcuts, Android NFC Tools/Tasker
Python Implementation with nfcpy
Installation
bash
pip install nfcpy
Reading NFC Tags
python
import nfc
from ndef import SmartPosterRecord

def read_nfc_tag():
    with nfc.ContactlessFrontend('usb') as clf:
        target = clf.sense(nfc.tag.tt3)
        tag = nfc.tag.activate(clf, target)
        
        if hasattr(tag, 'ndef'):
            for record in tag.ndef.records:
                if isinstance(record, SmartPosterRecord):
                    print(f"URL: {record.uri}")
                    print(f"Title: {record.title}")
        else:
            print("No NDEF data found")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    read_nfc_tag()
Writing NFC Tags
python
import nfc
import ndef

def write_nfc_tag():
    url = "https://github.com/tianjunrfid-dotcom"
    title = "GitHub Project"
    
    clf = nfc.ContactlessFrontend('usb')
    target = clf.sense(nfc.tag.tt3, timeout=0.5)
    
    if target:
        tag = nfc.tag.activate(clf, target)
        records = [ndef.SmartPosterRecord(uri=url, title=title)]
        tag.ndef.records = records
        print("Successfully written to tag")
    else:
        print("No tag detected")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    write_nfc_tag()
Security Best Practices
Data Validation:
Always validate NDEF payloads before processing
Use cryptographic signatures for sensitive data
python
import hashlib
def validate_payload(payload, signature):
    return hashlib.sha256(payload).digest() == signature
Password Protection:
python
# Enable password protection
tag.password = b"SecurePass"
tag.auth0 = 0x00  # Require authentication for all sectors
Secure Erasure:
python
# Lock memory sectors permanently
tag.lock_bytes(sector_range)
Common Use Cases
Automation with Smartphones
Android: Use NFC Tools to trigger Tasker automation
java
// Example Android NFC intent filter
<intent-filter>
    <action android:name="android.nfc.action.NDEF_DISCOVERED"/>
    <category android:name="android.intent.category.DEFAULT"/>
    <data android:mimeType="text/plain"/>
</intent-filter>
iOS: Configure Shortcuts app to execute actions on NFC scan
Contactless Payments
python
# Example payment data structure
payment_record = ndef.Record(
    tnf=ndef.TNF_WELL_KNOWN,
    rtype=b"pay",
    rdata=b"\x01\x00\x00\x00\x05\x00"  # Payment protocol header
)
Troubleshooting
Tag Detection Issues:
Ensure USB permissions with udev rules
sudo
echo 'SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTRS{idVendor}=="054c", MODE="0666"' | sudo tee /etc/udev/rules.d/nfc.rules
Data Corruption:
Implement CRC checks for critical data
python
import zlib
def add_crc(data):
    return data + bytes([zlib.crc32(data) & 0xFF])
